.pl 62
                            CHAPTER 4

                      INSTRUCTION OPERANDS

4.1  INTRODUCTION

The  syntax  of  instruction  operands are  desribed  in  detail. 
Instruction  operands  are operated on by CSD-32000  opcodes  and 
psuedo-ops. In the following example the opcode MOVW means move a 
16 bit integer. VAL1 and VAL2 are the instruction operands.  They 
identify  the source and destination for the number to be  moved.  
Instruction operands may be constants, memory addresses, symbols, 
and/or  expressions.

Example  ----->    MOVW  VAL1,VAL2

The following operand types exist:

               Operand Type                         Section

      General Operands                               4.2
        Register Operands                            4.2.1
        Register Relative Operands                   4.2.2
        Frame Memory Operands                        4.2.3
        Frame Memory Relative Operands               4.2.4
        Stack Memory Operands                        4.2.5
        Stack Memory Relative Operands               4.2.6
        Static Memory Operands                       4.2.7
        Static Memory Relative Operands              4.2.8
        Program Memory Operands                      4.2.9
        Immediate Operands                           4.2.10
        Absolute Operands                            4.2.11
        External Operands                            4.2.12
        Top of Stack Operands                        4.2.13
        Scaled-Index Byte Operands                   4.2.14
        Scaled-Index Word Operands                   4.2.15
        Scaled-Index Double-Word Operands            4.2.16
        Scaled-Index Quad-Word Operands              4.2.17
      Immediate subrange operands                    4.3
        Quick                                        4.3.1
        Block Length                                 4.3.2
        Bit Field Length                             4.3.3
        Bit Field Offset                             4.3.4
        Displacement Operands                        4.3.5
      Program Memory Operands                        4.4
      Register Operands                              4.5
      Register List Operand                          4.6
      Configuration List Operand                     4.7
      Processor Register Operands                    4.8
      Memory Management Register Operands            4.9
      External Procedure Operands                    4.10
4.2  General Operands

Format:   <gen>

description:
          <gen>          is   one   of  the   following   General 
                         Addressing Operand types:

                              Register
                              Register Relative
                              Frame Memory
                              Frame Memory Relative
                              Stack Memory
                              Stack Memory Relative
                              Static Memory
                              Static Memory Relative
                              Program Memory
                              Immediate
                              Absolute
                              External
                              Top of Stack
                              Scaled-Index Byte
                              Scaled-Index Word
                              Scaled-Index Double-Word
                              Scaled-Index Quad-Word

Many operands use displacements (disp) to specify the offset from 
a base address to a particular memory location.  The displacement 
range depends on the particular 32000 series microprocessor  that 
is in use.  The 32008,  32016 and 32032 currently have 24 address 
externally  and thus the displacement must range from -2**24+1 to 
2**24-1 (ie from -16777215 through to 16777215).  The newer 32000 
family  microprocessors have more external lines,  eg  the  32332 
carries  all out 32 address lines  and thus the displacement  can 
be  any value in the entire 30 bit range ie -2**29+1  through  to 
2**29+1.
Note.  The  assembler  computes all displacements to the full  30 
bits and thus can be used with any 32000 series microprocessor.

Subsections  4.2.1 through 4.2.17 detail the syntax and  function 
of each of the general operand types.
.pa
4.2.1  Register Operands

Format:   <register>

description:
          <register>     is  a symbol,  either reserved or  user-
                         defined,   with  register  type.    (See 
                         Section 2.6.3).

A  register  operand  specifies one  of  the  General-Purpose  or 
Floating-Point registers. 

Floating-Point  registers  are analogous to  the  General-Purpose 
registers  except  they  should only be used  for  Floating-Point 
instructions.

Example:

  RG5:   .EQU  R5
  FREG4: .EQU  F4
         MULF  FREG4,F6
         SUBW  RG5,R3

The  MULF  instruction  multipies a  floating-point  number  from 
Floating-Point  register   F4  with Floating-Point  register  F6.  
The SUBW instruction subtracts the low-order word of R5 from R3.
.pa
4.2.2.  Register Relative Operands

Format:   <disp>(<register>)

description:
          <disp>         is  a  displacement or expression  which 
                         must evaluate to an immediate type  with 
                         a   value  in  the  range  -16777215  to 
                         16777216.

	  (<register>)   is  a  symbol with  register  type  (see 
                         Section    2.6.3).    Parentheses    are 
                         required.

A  register  relative  operand specifies an operand at  a  memory 
address.  The address is the sum of the displacement disp and the 
contents of the General-Purpose register R<n>.

Examples:

  1.  MOVW  VALUE, 3(R4)
  2.  SUBB  (TWO*3)(R3), VALUE

In  example  1,   3(R4)  is  a  register  relative  operand.  The 
instruction moves the word at the address specified by the symbol 
VALUE to the memory location specified by 3(R4).

In  example 2,  (TWO*3)(R3) is a register relative  operand.  The 
expression TWO * 3 must evaluate to an immediate type. This value 
is  added  to the contents of register R3 to yield the  operand's 
address.  The instruction subtracts the byte at this address from 
the byte at the address specified by the symbol VALUE. The result 
is stored at VALUE.
.pa
4.2.3  Frame Memory Operands

Format:  <disp>(FP)

description:
          <disp>         is  a  displacement or expression  which 
                         must evaluate to an Immediate type  with 
                         a  value  that  is legal for  the  32000 
                         series microprocessor in use.

          (FP)           specifies  the  Frame-Pointer  register.  
                         Parentheses are required.

A  frame memory operand specifies an operand at a memory address. 
The address is the sum of the displacement disp and the  contents 
of the FP register.

A  symbol  may be used as a frame-memory operand if it  has  been 
defined as FP type (see Section 2.6.3).

Examples:

  1.  MOVW  VALUE, 12(FP)
  2.  SUBB  (TWO*3)(FP), VALUE

In example 1,  12(FP) is a frame memory operand.  The instruction 
moves  the  word at the address specified by the symbol VALUE  to 
the word at the memory address specified by 12(FP).

In  example  2,  (TWO*3)(FP)  is  a  frame  memory  operand.  The 
expression  (TWO*3)  must evaluate to an  immediate  value.  This 
value  is  added  to the contents of register  FP  to  yield  the 
operand's  address.  The  instruction subtracts the byte at  this 
address  from  the byte at the address specified  by  the  symbol 
VALUE.  The result is stored at VALUE.
.pa
4.2.4  Frame memory Relative Operands

Format:   <disp>(<expression>)

description:
          <disp>         is  a  displacement or expression  which 
                         must evaluate to an Immediate type  with 
                         a  value  that  is legal for  the  32000 
                         series microprocessor in use.

          (<expression>) is  an expression with FP relative  type 
                         (see  Section 2.6.3).   Parentheses  are 
                         required.

A  frame memory relative operand points to a memory address whose 
double-word  value  is  added to the  displacement  to  give  the 
resultant address.

Example:

	FP_VAL:	.EQU	12(FP)
		ADDB	R3,12(5(FP)+1)
		MOVB	3(FP_VAL),R4

In  the  above  example 12(5(FP)+1) is a  frame  memory  relative 
operand.   The  second assembler instruction adds register R3  to 
the  specified  address.   The address is the sum of 12  and  the 
double-word value at the address (5(FP+1)) ie (6(FP)). The symbol 
FP_VAL  is  defined as FP relative in the  first  statement.  The 
third  statement  moves a byte from the double-word at  offset  3 
from FP_VAL to R4.
.pa
4.2.5  Stack Memory Operands

Format:   <disp>(SP)

description:
          <disp>         is  a  displacement or expression  which 
                         must evaluate to an Immediate type  with 
                         a  value  that  is legal for  the  32000 
                         series microprocessor in use.

          (SP)           specifies  the  current  stack  pointer.  
                         Parentheses are required.

A  stack memory operand specifies an operand at a memory address. 
The  address is computed as the sum of the displacement disp  and 
the contents of the current stack pointer register.

A  symbol  may be used as a stack memory operand if it  has  been 
defined as an SP type (see Section 2.6.8).

Examples:

  1.  MOVW  VALUE, 12(SP)
  2.  SUBB  (TWO*3)(SP), VALUE

In example 1,  12(SP) is a stack memory operand.  The instruction 
moves  the word at the address specified by the symbol  VALUE  to 
the   memory  address  specified  by  12(SP).

In  example  2,  (TWO*3)(SP)  is  a  stack  memory  operand.  The 
expression  (TWO*3)  must evaluate to an  immediate  value.  This 
value  is  added  to  the contents of register SP  to  yield  the 
operand's  address.  The instruction subtracts the byte  at  this 
address  from  the  byte at the address specified by  the  symbol 
VALUE. The result is stored at VALUE.
.pa
4.2.6  Stack Memory Relative Operands

Format:   <disp>(<expression>)

description:
          <disp>         is  a  displacement or expression  which 
                         must evaluate to an Immediate type  with 
                         a  value  that  is legal for  the  32000 
                         series microprocessor in use.

          <expression>   should be an expression with SP relative 
                         type  (see Section 2.6.8).   Parentheses 
                         are required.

A stack memory relative operand points to a memory address  whose 
double-word  value  is  added  to the displacement  to  give  the 
resultant address.

Example:

	SP_VAL:	.EQU	12(SP)
		ADDB	R3,12(5(SP)+1)
		MOVB	3(SP_VAL),R4

In  the  above  example 12(5(SP)+1) is a  stack  memory  relative 
operand.   The  second assembler instruction adds register R3  to 
the  specified  address.   The address is the sum of 12  and  the 
double-word value at the address (5(SP+1)) ie (6(SP)). The symbol 
SP_VAL  is  defined as SP relative in the  first  statement.  The 
third  statement  moves a byte from the double-word at  offset  3 
from SP_VAL to R4.
.pa
4.2.7  Static Memory Operands

Format:   <disp>(SB)

description:
          <disp>         is  a  displacement or expression  which 
                         must evaluate to an Immediate type  with 
                         a  value  that  is legal for  the  32000 
                         series microprocessor in use.

          (SB)           specifies   the  Static  Base  register.  
                         Parentheses are required.

A   static  memory  operand  specifies an  operand  at  a  memory 
address.  The address  is  the  sum  of the displacement disp and 
the contents of the Static Base register.

A  symbol may be used as a static memory operand if it has been defined
as an SB type (see Section 2.6.6).

Examples:

  1.  MOVW  VALUE, 12(SB)
  2.  SUBB  (TWO*3)(SB), VALUE

In example 1, 12(SB) is a static memory operand.  The instruction 
moves  the  word at the address specified by the symbol VALUE  to 
the word at the memory address specified by 12(SB).

In  example  2,  (TWO*3)(SB)  is a  static  memory  operand.  The 
expression  (TWO*3)  must evaluate to an  immediate  value.  This 
value  is  added  to the contents of register  SB  to  yield  the 
operand's  address.  The  instruction subtracts the byte at  this 
address  from  the byte at the address specified  by  the  symbol 
VALUE. The result is stored at VALUE.
.pa
4.2.8  Static Memory Relative Operands

Format:   <disp>(<expression>)

description:
          <disp>         is  a  displacement or expression  which 
                         must evaluate to an Immediate type  with 
                         a  value  that  is legal for  the  32000 
                         series microprocessor in use.

          <expression>   should  be  expression with SB  relative 
                         type (see Section  2.6.6).   Parentheses 
                         are required

A static memory relative operand points to a memory address whose 
double-word  value  is  added  to the displacement  to  give  the 
resultant address.

Example:

	SB_VAL:	.EQU	12(SB)
		ADDB	R3,12(5(SB)+1)
		MOVB	3(SB_VAL),R4

In  the  above example 12(5(SB)+1) is a  static  memory  relative 
operand.   The  second assembler instruction adds register R3  to 
the  specified  address.   The address is the sum of 12  and  the 
double-word value at the address (5(SB+1)) ie (6(SB)). The symbol 
SB_VAL  is  defined as SB relative in the  first  statement.  The 
third  statement  moves a byte from the double-word at  offset  3 
from SB_VAL to R4.
.pa
4.2.9  Program Memory Operands

Format:   <disp>(PC)

description:
          <disp>         is  a  displacement or expression  which 
                         must evaluate to an Immediate type  with 
                         a  value  that  is legal for  the  32000 
                         series microprocessor in use.

          (PC)           specifies   the  start  address  of  the 
                         program  code  of  the  current  module.  
                         Parentheses are required.

A  program  memory  operand  specifies an  operand  at  a  memory 
address.   The address  is  the  sum of the displacement disp and 
the start address of the program code segment of the module.

A  symbol may be used as a program memory operand if it has  been 
defined as PC type (see Section 2.6.9).

Examples:

  1.  MOVW  VALUE, 12(PC)
  2.  SUBB  (TWO*3)(PC), VALUE

In  example  1,   12(PC)  is  a  program  memory  operand.    The 
instruction moves the word at the address specified by the symbol 
VALUE to the word at the memory address specified by 12(PC).

In  example  2,  (TWO*3)(PC)  is a program  memory  operand.  The 
expression  (TWO*3)  must evaluate to an  immediate  value.  This 
value  is  added  to the contents of register  PC  to  yield  the 
operand's  address.  The  instruction subtracts the byte at  this 
address  from  the byte at the address specified  by  the  symbol 
VALUE. The result is stored at VALUE.

Program  memory  operands are encoded as  PC-relative  addressing 
mode.   At  run time the address of a PC relative operand is  the 
encoded  displacement plus the contents of the PC register.  Thus 
the  Assembler  encodes  the  difference  between  the  operand's 
displacement  and the value of the location counter (as a  signed 
number), rather than the value of the displacement itself.
.pa
4.2.10  Immediate Operands

Format:   <expression>

description:
          <expression>   is one of the following:

          - an expression of type immediate (see Section 2.6.1)
          - an expression of type long (see Section 2.6.2)

Immediate  operands are encoded into immediate  addressing  mode, 
thus the operand's value is stored in the instruction stream.

The   range   of   immediate  operands  is  controlled   by   the 
instruction's length specifiers as follows:

  - For expressions of type immediate, the ranges are:
	-128 to 255			for byte instructions.
	-32768 to 65535			for word instructions.
	-2147483648 to 2147483648	for double-word instructions.

  - For expressions of type long, the positive ranges are:
         1.28x10E-38 to 3.40x10E38	for float instructions.
         2.23x10E-308 to 1.80x10E308	for long instructions.


Examples:

  1.  ADDW  3, FRED
  2.  SUBF  3.14159E12, F2
  3.  SUBD  "MNOP", TEST
  4.  ADDD  TWO*3, R4

Example  1  adds  the  word  constant 5  to  the  memory  address 
specified by FRED.

Example 2 subtracts the floating point number 3.14159E12 from the 
contents of register F2.

Example  3 subtracts the string constant "MNOP" from the  double-
word at address specified by TEST.

Example  4 adds the value of the expression TWO*3 to the  double-
word of register R4.
.pa
4.2.11  Absolute Operands

Format:  <absolute>

description: 
          <absolute>     is  a  constant or an  expression  which 
                         evaluates to absolute type (see  Section 
                         2.6.4).

An  absolute  operand specifies an operand at an absolute  memory 
address.

Examples:

  1.		SUBW  H'9876, @12
  2.		CMPB  @ELEVEN, R6
  3.  HERE:	.EQU @12
 		MOVW  HERE, R3

In  example  1,  @12  is an  absolute  operand.  The  instruction 
subtracts the immediate operand H'9876 from the word starting  at 
absolute address 12.

In example 2,  @ELEVEN is an absolute operand.  The symbol ELEVEN 
must  be of immediate type.  The instruction compares the word at 
the absolute address specified by ELEVEN to the low order word of 
register R6.

In  example 3,  the use of @ preceding an immediate value  causes 
the .EQU directive to assign HERE absolute type.  MOVW then moves 
the word at the absolute  address  specified  by HERE to the low-
order word of register R3.
.pa
4.2.12  External Operands

Format:   <external>

description:
          <external>     is an expression with external type (see 
                         Section 2.6.5).

An  external  operand  implies both a Link  Table  entry  and  an 
offset.  At run-time the contents of the Link Table entry and the 
offset are added together to produce an absolute address.

Examples:

  1.  ADDW  R3, EXT(4)
  2.  SUBW  FIRST, EXT(FOUR) + ELEVEN

In  example 1,  EXT(4) is an external operand.   The  instruction 
adds  the low order word of register R3 to the word specified  by 
EXT(3).  The  external   address is the sum  of  the  double-word 
contents of a Link Table entry and 0.

In  example  2,  EXT(FOUR) + ELEVEN is an external  operand.  The 
instruction subtracts the word at the address specified by  FIRST 
from  the word specified by EXT(FOUR) + ELEVEN.  The symbols FOUR 
and ELEVEN must evaluate to immediate type.
.pa
4.2.13  Top of Stack Operands

Format:   TOS

description:
          TOS       is the required keyword.

The  top  of stack operand specifies an operand which is  at  the 
current  top  of stack,  ie the address specified by the  current 
stack pointer. 

TOS is a NS32000 general addressing mode.

The stack pointer is incremented by the length (in bytes) of  the 
operand  after  a  read  is  performed.   The  stack  pointer  is 
decremented  by  the  length (in bytes) of the operand  before  a 
write  is  performed.  The stack pointer is not  modified  if  an 
operand is both read and written.

Examples:

  1.  ADDW  R4,TOS
  2.  SUBW  TOS,TOS

Example  1  decrements the stack pointer by 2 (the  length  of  a 
word)  and then adds the low-order word of register R4 to the top 
of the stack.

Example  2  reads  the  word at the top  of  the  current  stack, 
increments  the stack pointer by 2 (the length of a word),  reads 
the  word at the new top of stack,  subtracts the first word from 
the  second  word and then writes the word back over  the  second 
word.
.pa
4.2.14  Scaled-Index Byte Operands

Format:   gen[<register>:B]

description:
          gen            specifies a general operand.  It may not 
                         be   an  immediate  operand  or  another 
                         scaled-index operand.

	   []            are the required brackets.

	    <register>   specifies  a  General-Purpose   register 
                         either by using R<n>,  ie.  one of R0 to 
                         R7,  or  by using a symbol with register 
                         type.

	   :B            is the byte scaling flag.

The  resulting address of this addressing mode is the sum of  the 
address  of  the general operand 'gen' and the  contents  of  the 
General-Purpose register R<n> multiplied by 1.

Example:

  ADDW  R4, 20(FP)[R3:B]

In  the  above  example,  20(FP)[R3:B]  is  a  scaled-index  byte 
operand.  The  instruction adds the low-order word of register R4 
to  the  contents of the  destination  address.  The  destination 
address  is  the sum of the address specified by 20(FP)  and  the 
contents of the register R3 multiplied by 1.
.pa
4.2.15  Scaled-Index Word Operands

Format:   gen[<register>:W]

description:
          gen            specifies a general operand.  It may not 
                         be   an  immediate  operand  or  another 
                         scaled-index operand.

          []             are the required brackets.

          <register>     specifies  a  General-Purpose   register 
                         either by using R<n>,  ie.  one of R0 to 
                         R7,  or  by using a symbol with register 
                         type.

          :W             is the word scaling flag.

The  resulting address of this addressing mode is the sum of  the 
address  of  the general operand 'gen' and the  contents  of  the 
General-Purpose register R<n> multiplied by 2.

Example:

  ADDW  R4, 20(FP)[R3:W]

In  the  above  example,  20(FP)[R3:W]  is  a  scaled-index  word 
operand.  The  instruction adds the low-order word of register R4 
to  the  contents  of the destination  address.  The  destination 
address  is  the sum of the address specified by 20(FP)  and  the 
contents of the register R3 multiplied by 2.
.pa
4.2.16  Scaled-Index Double-Word Operands

Format:   gen[<register>:D]

description:
          gen            specifies a general operand.  It may not 
                         be   an  immediate  operand  or  another 
                         scaled-index operand.

          []             are the required brackets.

          <register>     specifies  a  General-Purpose   register 
                         either by using R<n>,  ie.  one of R0 to 
                         R7,  or  by using a symbol with register 
                         type.

          :D             is the double-word scaling flag.

The  resulting address of this addressing mode is the sum of  the 
address  of  the general operand 'gen' and the  contents  of  the 
General-Purpose register R<n> multiplied by 4.

Example:

  ADDW  R4, 20(FP)[R3:D]

In the above example,  20(FP)[R3:D] is a scaled-index double word 
operand.   The instruction adds the low-order word of register R4 
to  the  contents of the  destination  address.  The  destination 
address  is  the sum of the address specified by 20(FP)  and  the 
contents of the register R3 multiplied by 4.
.pa
4.2.17  Scaled-Index Quad-Word Operands

Format:   gen[<register>:Q]

description:
          gen            specifies a general operand.  It may not 
                         be  an  immediate  operand  or   another 
                         scaled-index operand.

          []             are the required brackets.

          <register>     specifies   a  General-Purpose  register 
                         either by using R<n>,  ie.  one of R0 to 
                         R7,  or by using a symbol with  register 
                         type.

          :Q             is the quad-word scaling flag.

The  resulting address of this addressing mode is the sum of  the 
address  of  the  general operand 'gen' and the contents  of  the 
General-Purpose register R<n> multiplied by 8.

Example:

  ADDW  R4, 20(FP)[R3:Q]

In  the above example,  20(FP)[R3:Q] is a scaled-index  quad-word 
operand.   The instruction adds the low-order word of register R4 
to  the  contents  of the destination  address.  The  destination 
address  is  the sum of the address specified by 20(FP)  and  the 
contents of the register R3 multiplied by 8.
.pa
4.3  IMMEDIATE OPERANDS

Immediate  operands are expressions of immediate type with values 
within subranges of the full double-word range (32 bits).


4.3.1  Quick Operands

Format:   <quick>

description:
          <quick>        is a signed constant or expression which 
                         evaluates  to an immediate type  with  a 
                         value in the range -8 to 7, inclusive.

A  quick  operand  is  encoded as a 4-bit  signed  integer  in  a 
reserved field within the instruction itself.  Quick operands may 
only be used in the quick-integer instructions. The quick operand 
is  typically used to clear,  increment,  decrement or compare  a 
variable.

Examples:

  1.  MOVQB  -1, LAST(R4)
  2.  CMPQB   2, TEST
  3.  ADDQD  1, R4

Example  1  moves  the  quick operand -1 to the  operand  at  the 
address specified by LAST(R4).

Example 2 compares the quick operand 2 with the operand specified 
by TEST.

Example 3 adds the quick operand 1 to the double-word of register 
R4.  This would effectively increment register R4.
.pa
4.3.2  Block Length Operands

Format:   <cons4>

description:
          <const>        is  an  unsigned constant or  expression 
                         which  evaluates  to an  immediate  type 
                         with  a value in the range 1 to 16  (see 
                         below).

The  block  length  operands are  4-bit  unsigned  numbers  which 
specify  the  length of a block of integers.  A block may  be  no 
longer than 16 bytes,  thus the allowable values that <cons4> may 
take depends on the instruction's length specifier (B,  W,  or D) 
as shown by the following:

        Length Specifier        <cons4>
        ----------------        -------
		B		1 to 16
		W		1 to 8
		D		1 to 4

The operand is multiplied by the corresponding byte length of the 
length specifier and then decremented by one before being encoded 
in the instruction.

The  block length operand is the final operand in  the  following 
instructions:

  Move Multiple      MOVMi
  Compare Multiple   CMPMi

Examples:

  1.  MOVMB   VAL1, R0, 4
  2.  CMPMD   VAL2, R4, LENGTH/4

In example 1, the block length 4 specifies the number of bytes to 
move from the address specified by VAL1 to the address  specified 
by R0.

In  example 2,  the block length is the expression  LENGTH/4.  It 
specifies  the  number of double-words to be  compared.  LENGTH/4 
must evaluate to a positive number less than, or equal to four.

NOTE:     the  block instructions compute an address for the  two 
          general addressing fields,  thus the contents of R0 and 
          R4 are used as addresses.
.pa
4.3.3  Bit-Field Length Operands

Format:   <cons5>

description:
          <cons5>        is  an  unsigned constant or  expression 
                         which  evaluates  to an  immediate  type 
                         with  a value in the range 1 to  32.  At 
                         assembly-time,  the assembler decrements 
                         the number by 1 before encoding it  into 
                         the instruction.

A  bit-field  length operand is an unsigned,  5-bit number  which 
specifies  the  length in a  bit-field  instruction.  The  length 
operands of the 'short bit field' instructions are encoded into a 
5-bit field,  and into a byte displacement in the other bit-field 
instructions. The bit-field length operand is the last operand in 
the following instructions:

  Extract Field Short  EXTSi
  Insert Field Short   INSSi

Examples:

  1.  EXTSB  START, TARGET, 4, 10
  2.  INSSW  BEG, END, 8, 13

In example 1,  10 is the 5-bit constant. The instruction computes 
the  location of a bit field 10 bits in length and 4 bits  offset 
from  the address specified by START and copies the field to  the 
address specified by the symbol TARGET.

In example 2,  13 is the 5-bit constant. The instruction computes 
the  destination  of  a bit field 13 bits in length  and  8  bits 
offset from the address specified by END and moves the field from 
the address specified by BEG to the destination.
.pa
4.3.4  Bit-Field Offset Operands

Format:   <cons3>

description:
          <cons3>        is  an unsigned constant  or  expression 
                         which  evaluates  to an  immediate  type 
                         with a value in the range 0 to 7.

A  bit-field  offset  operand is a  3-bit,  unsigned  number.  It 
specifies an offset which is used to calculate the location of  a 
bit field. A bit-field offset operand is the third operand in the 
following instructions:

  Extract Field Short   EXTSi
  Insert Field Short    INSSi

Examples:

  1.  EXTSB  START, END, 4, 6
  2.  INSSW  BEG, END, 3, 12

In example 1, 4 is a 3-bit constant. The instruction computes the 
source address by adding the bit offset 4 to START and moving a 6 
bit field to the destination END, the top 4 bits are zero filled.

In example 2, 3 is a 3-bit constant. The instruction computes the 
target  address  by  adding  the bit  offset  3  to  the  address 
specified by END, and moves a field 12 bits in length from BEG.
.pa
4.3.5  Displacement Operands

Format:   <disp>

description:
          <disp>         is  a  displacement or expression  which 
                         must evaluate to an Immediate type  with 
                         a  value  that  is legal for  the  32000 
                         series microprocessor in use.

A  displacement  operand  is the final operand in  the  following 
instructions:

	Return from Subroutine		RET
	Return from Trap		RETT
	Insert Field			EXTi

Examples:

  1.  RET	4
  2.  RETT	3
  3.  INSW	R3, R4, 4(R3), 5

In example 1,  the displacement is 4.  It specifies the number of 
bytes to remove from the stack on return from a subroutine.

In example 2,  the displacement is 3.  It specifies the number of 
bytes to remove from the stack on return from a trap.

In example 3,  the displacement is 5.  It specifies the number of 
bits in the bit field to be written.

Displacement  operands are encoded by the assembler in  the  same 
way  as  memory displacements are.  The length of a  displacement 
operand is encoded in the most significant bits of the operand in 
the following way:

  0XXXXXXX					1 byte
  10XXXXXX XXXXXXXX				2 bytes
  11XXXXXX XXXXXXXX XXXXXXXX XXXXXXXX		4 bytes

Note.  The displacement is output with the most significant bytes 
first.
.pa
4.4  PROGRAM MEMORY OPERANDS

Format:   <label>

description:
          <label>        is a label or expression which evaluates 
                         to  a PC-relative type with a  value  in 
                         the range -16777215 through 16777216.

A  label  operand specifies the location of  an  instruction.  At 
assembly-time  the  assembler  computes the address as  a  signed 
number which is the distance in bytes from the specified label to 
the current instruction address.

Program  memory operands are stored in memory in the same way  as 
general program memory operands (Section 4.2.9).

  Branch to subroutine		BSR
  Jump to subroutine		JSR
  Conditional branch		B[cond] 

Examples:

  1.  BSR	FRED
  2.  JSR	13(PC)
  3.  BEQ	$+6

In example 1,  the label operand is FRED. It specifies the number 
of bytes offset from the PC.

In example 2,  the displacement is 13. It specifies the number of 
bytes offset from the PC.

In example 3,  the displacement is 6.  It specifies the number of 
bytes offset from the beginning of the current instruction.
.pa
4.5  REGISTER OPERANDS

Format:   <register>

description:
          <register>     is  a General-Purpose register specified 
                         by either R<n>,  ie.  one of R0  through 
                         R7, or a symbol with register type.

A   register   operand  specifies  one  of  the   General-Purpose 
registers. The contents of the register are used as the operand.

  Move				MOVi
  Add				ADDi
  Compare multiple		CMPMi

Register operands are equivalent to the general register operands 
(see Section 4.2.1).

Examples:

  1.  MOVB	R0, 12(FP)
  2.  ADDW	R3, 5(SP)
  3.  CMPMB	R2, FRED, LENGTH

In  example  1,  the  register operand is  R0.  The  contents  of 
register R0 moved to the address computed from 12 added to the FP 
register.

In  example  2,  the  register operand is  R3.  The  contents  of 
register R3 is added to the word contents at the address computed 
from 5 added to the current stack pointer.

In  example  3,  the  register operand is  R2.  The  contents  of 
register  R2  is  compared with LENGTH bytes at  the  address  of 
symbol FRED.
.pa
4.6  REGISTER LIST (reglist) OPERAND

Format:   [[<register>,,,]]

description: 
          []             are  the  required  brackets.  A  single 
                         level  of brackets are required even  if 
                         no registers are specified.

          <register>     specifies  a General-Purpose register or 
                         a symbol with register type.

A   register  list  operand  may  be  used  with  the   following 
instructions:

  Save Registers        SAVE
  Restore Registers     RESTORE
  Enter New Context     ENTER
  Exit Context          EXIT

Examples:

  1.  FRED:	.EQU  R5
		SAVE     [FRED]
  2.		RESTORE  [R3]
  3.		ENTER    [], 3
  4.		EXIT     [R0,R1]

In example 1, the operand specifies a single register FRED, which 
has  been  set to R5.  The contents of register R5 are  saved  on 
stack.

In  example 2,  the operand specifies the register directly.  The 
instruction removes a double-word off the stack into R3.

In example 3,  the operand specifies no registers. A displacement 
of 5 is used to allocate three bytes of the stack for storage.

In example 4, the operand restores two General-Purpose registers, 
R0 and R1, and then the EXIT instruction is executed.
.pa
4.7  CONFIGURATION LIST (cfglist) OPERAND

Format:   [[C] [,I] [,M] [,F]]

description:
          []             are the required brackets.  The brackets 
                         must be entered even if no configuration 
                         bit is specified.

          C     specifies that a Custom Slave is installed.
	  I     specifies that a Interrupt Control Unit is installed.
	  M     specifies that a Memory Management Unit is installed.
	  F     specifies that a Floating Point Unit is installed.

               		 If  one  or  more  of  these  units  are                         
                         installed, then the  user program should                         
                         set   the  corresponding  bits  in   the 
                         NS32032  Configuration register is  set. 
                         Otherwise,  the  bit  is  cleared.   Any 
                         order  is  permissible as  long  as  bit 
                         specifications  are separated by commas.


A  configuration  list  operand may be used  with  the  following 
instruction:

  Set Configuration Register   SETCFG

Examples:

  1.  SETCFG []
  2.  SETCFG [I]
  3.  SETCFG [C,I,M,F]

In  example  1,  the operand specifies  no  register  bits.   The 
instruction clears all bits in the Configuration register.

In example 2,  the operand specifies the I bit.   The instruction 
sets the I bit and clears the F, M, and C bits.

In  example 3,  the operand specifies all bits.   The instruction 
sets all bits in the Configuration register.

NOTE:     If a bit is set when the unit is not  present,  serious 
          hardware problems can occur.
.pa
4.8  PROCESSOR REGISTER OPERANDS

Format:   <proceg>

description:
          <proceg>       specifies one of the following dedicated 
                         CPU registers:

               UPSR        User Processor Status Register
               FP          Frame Pointer
               SP          Stack Pointer
               SB          Static Base
               PSR         Processor Status Register
               INTBASE     Interrupt Base
               MOD         Module

                         The   function  of  the  Dedicated   CPU 
                         Registers is described in Section 1.3.2.

The  first operand in the following instructions is  a  processor 
register operand.

  Load Processor Register   LPRi
  Store Processor Register  SPRi

Examples:

  1.  LPRD  SB, R7
  2.  SPRD  INTBASE, INT_SAVE

In  example  1,  SB  is  the  Processor  register  operand.   The 
instruction  copies  the  double-word in register R7  to  the  SB 
register.

In  example 2,  INTBASE is the Processor register  operand.   The 
instruction copies the double-word of the Interrupt Base register 
to the address specified by the symbol INT_SAVE.
.pa
4.9   MEMORY MANAGEMENT REGISTER OPERANDS

Format:   <mmureg>

description:
          <mmureg>       specifies  one of the  following  Memory 
                         Management registers:

              BPR0    Breakpoint Register 0
              BPR1    Breakpoint Register 1
              PF0     Program Flow 0
              PF1     Program Flow 1
              BCNT    Breakpoint Count
              PTB0    Page Table Base 0
              PTB1    Page Table Base 1
              SC0     Sequential Count 0
              SC1     Sequential Count 1
              MSR     Memory Management Status Register
              EIA     Error/Invalidate Address

                         Memory    Management    registers    are 
                         described in Section 1.3.4.

The  first  operand  in the following instructions  is  a  Memory 
management register.

  Load Memory Management Register     LMR
  Store Memory Management             SMR

Examples:

  1.  LMR  EIA,	R0
  2.  SMR  PF0, PFLOW_1

In example 1,  EIA is the memory management register operand. The 
instruction loads the double-word in R0 into the Error/Invalidate 
Address register.

In example 2,  PF0 is the memory management register operand. The 
instruction  stores  the double-word contents of the PF0  at  the 
address specified by the symbol PFLOW_1.
.pa
4.10  EXTERNAL PROCEDURE OPERANDS

Format:   <external>

description:
          <external>     is  a symbol or expression with external 
                         type and zero offset.

An  external  procedure  operand  specifies an entry in the  Link 
Table.    Entries    for    external    procedure    are   called  
external  procedure descriptors and consist of the 16-bit address 
of  an  entry  in  the  Module Table   and   a   16-bit   offset.    
During   execution   the  address of the  external  procedure  is 
calculated  by  adding the offset to the address in  the   Module  
Table   entry  (See  the  section  on  software  modules  in  the 
Programmer's Reference Manual).

An  external  operand  is  the  only  operand  in  the  following 
instructions:

  Call External Procedure               CXP
  Call External Procedure descriptor    CXPD

Example:

  CXP   PRINTF

In the example,  PRINTF is an external operand. PRINTF references 
a  Link  Table  entry address.  At assemble  time  the  Assembler 
assigns a number to the PRINTF label.  At run-time the Link Table 
address is extracted from the current Module Table,  the value of 
the PRINTF label is multiplied by four and a double-word is  read 
from  this  address.  The low-order word is the new Module  Table 
address  and  the  high-order word is the  offset  to  the  start 
address of the procedure being called. The offset is added to the 
module's  code  address which is obtained from the  new  module's 
Module Table.

